For Kant, anarchy falls short of the moral framework necessary for a just society. Anarchy, characterized by the absence of a centralized authority or government, lacks the structure and enforcement mechanisms needed to uphold individual rights and maintain societal order according to Kantian ethics. Kant believed that a legitimate government, guided by the rule of law and moral principles, is essential to protect human dignity, ensure fairness, and prevent chaos. In his view, anarchy fails to provide the necessary conditions for respecting the autonomy and rationality of individuals, ultimately falling short of establishing a just and ethical society.
