Egoist anarchism or anarcho-egoism, often shortened as "egoist anarchism," is a philosophical perspective that emphasizes the importance of individual autonomy and self-interest in the context of an anarchist society. Followers of egoist anarchism, such as Max Stirner, believe that individuals should prioritize their own well-being and desires above all else, rejecting external authorities and moral constraints. While this perspective can empower individuals to assert their autonomy and challenge oppressive systems, critics argue that an exclusive focus on self-interest may undermine collective solidarity and the pursuit of common goals in a society. Egoist anarchism raises important questions about the balance between individual freedom and community welfare within anarchist thought.
Expropriative anarchism is the name given to a radical form of anarchism that advocates for the seizure of property from the ruling class and redistribution among the community. It challenges the concept of private ownership and aims to dismantle hierarchies embedded in capitalist structures. While some see expropriative anarchism as a necessary means to achieve equality and justice, others criticize it for its potential to incite violence and chaos.
