Independence anarchism or anarcho-independentism is an anarchist philosophy that emphasizes individual autonomy and self-governance as key principles. It values personal freedom, voluntary cooperation, and decentralized decision-making, advocating for a society where individuals have the power to govern themselves without hierarchical structures or external authority. While promoting individual sovereignty, independence anarchism also recognizes the importance of collective action and mutual aid in achieving a harmonious and equitable community. This philosophy challenges traditional notions of government and hierarchy, envisioning a society based on voluntary associations and direct democracy.
Being grounded in such concepts, independence anarchism focuses on individual autonomy and self-governance, challenging traditional hierarchies and structures. It advocates for a society based on voluntary cooperation and mutual aid, where individuals are free from oppressive systems and able to live according to their own values and beliefs. While some see it as a path to true freedom and equality, others view it as unrealistic and potentially chaotic, questioning its ability to address complex social issues and ensure collective well-being.
